    "John T. Carroll": "who offer the model response (2:20). They go beyond wonder to praise. The `[group_Word_Luk_1]`\npresence of unnamed others with Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` and his parents parallels the account\nof John `[char_John_Ref]`\u2019s birth and naming, where relatives and neighbors were present and\n\u201ceveryone who heard\u201d reacted to the news (1:58\u201366). The `[group_Word_Luk_1]` role played by an\nobserving public was more complex and significant in that scene, for that name-\nless crowd first set an obstacle and test to fidelity before John `[char_John_Ref]`\u2019s parents, then\n(in wider circles) expressed both fear and pondering questioning (1:65\u201366),\nreactions comparable to those apportioned between Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]` (pondering, 2:19) and\neveryone else (amazement,\nv. 20).",
    "John Trapp": "As it was told unto them ] God, to show that he respected not persons, revealed this grand mystery to shepherds and wise men; the one poor, the other rich; the one learned, the other unlearned; the one Jews, the other Gentiles; the one near, the other far off.\nVer.\n20. As it was told unto them] God, to show that he respected not persons, revealed this grand mystery to shepherds and wise men; the one poor, the other rich; the one learned, the other unlearned; the one Jews, the other Gentiles; the one near, the other far off.\nVer.\n20. Ver.\n20. Forty and six years ] All, save what lacks; for it was six years\u2019 work only, but they reckon the interim of interruption, #Ezr 3:1-7:28 , to aggravate the matter. So they are not only blinded, but hardened.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 141": "Ft388 --  Targum in Ruth i,"
